.SH FONT CACHE
After installing or removing fonts, the system font cache should be updated:
.PP
.RS 4
# fontmgr automatically updates cache, but you can also run:
.br
fontmgr makecache
.br
# Or use system tools:
.br
fc-cache -fv
.RE
.PP
Applications may need to be restarted to detect newly installed fonts.
.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
Font installations are managed through preconfigured GitHub repositories under the fontmgr organization
.IP \(bu 2
Each font package includes TrueType or OpenType font files and installation scripts
.IP \(bu 2
Fonts are installed to user directories by default (~/.local/share/fonts)
.IP \(bu 2
System-wide installation may require root privileges
.IP \(bu 2
Font cache is automatically updated after installation when using makecache
.IP \(bu 2
Installed fonts are tracked in ~/.local/share/CasjaysDev/apps/fontmgr/
.IP \(bu 2
Desktop notifications can be disabled by setting FONTMGR_NOTIFY_ENABLED=no
.IP \(bu 2
GitHub authentication token enables access to complete font repository list
.IP \(bu 2
Programming fonts with ligatures require application support for ligature rendering
.SH PROGRAMMING LIGATURES
Programming ligatures combine multiple characters into single glyphs for better readability:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
Common ligatures:
  ->  becomes →
  =>  becomes ⇒
  >=  becomes ≥
  <=  becomes ≤
  !=  becomes ≠
  ==  becomes ==
  ===  becomes ≡
.EE
.RE
.PP
Not all editors and terminals support ligatures. Popular applications with ligature support include VS Code, Sublime Text, Kitty, and Alacritty.
